comments.text:
The following lemma is obvious but potentially useful in iteratively lower bounding $f(a,p)$: let $P(a,p,N)$ denote the assertion that $p^{
u_p(N!)} | a_1! + \dots + a_n!$ for some $a=a_1 < a_2 < \dots < a_n < N$. Then, if the $2^H$ subset sums of $N!/p^{
u_p(N!)}, \dots, (N+H-1)!/p^{
u_p(N!)}$ cover all the residue classes of ${ f Z}/p^{
u_p((N+H)!/N!)}{ f Z}$, $P(a,p,N)$ implies $P(a,p,N+H)$. For instance this shows that $P(a,p,N)$ implies $P(a,p,N+1)$ whenever $N+1$ is not divisible by $p$, and for many $p$ (e.g., $p=5$) it should be possible to show computationally that $P(a,p,N)$ implies $P(a,p,N+p)$ whenever $N+p$ is divisible by exactly one power of $p$ by showing that the $2^p$ subset sums of $0!, 1!, \dots, (p-1)!$ cover all of ${ f Z}/p{ f Z}$. More generally, some finite computation seems to let one show that $P(a,p,N)$ implies $P(a,p,N+p^j)$ whenever $N+p^j$ is divisible by exactly $j$ powers of $p$ for any fixed $j$ (with the $N=0$ case being key); doing this for $j \leq J$ should already get some lower bound of the shape $f(a,p) \geq 
u_p( (p^{J+1}-1)! )$.
